1.Ensure that the title, author list, affiliation, email, and copyright license are consistent across the submitted paper, HotCRP, and the e-right form. Note that these meta data cannot be changed unless the changes are approved by the track chairs with valid
 reasons. If you submitted incorrect author information, affiliation, and email in the e-right form, please contact the track chairs and proceeding chair immediately.

2.Make sure to include ACM keywords on your HotCRP page.

3.Make sure to include ACM Computing Classification on your HotCRP page.

4.Make sure to include References on your HotCRP page.

5.Make sure to submit the source files of your camera-ready version

6.Make sure that all the authors provide their ORCID. This needs to be provided in the account settings of each author on HotCRP.

7.Make sure to use the latest version of the ACM template as described here:  https://conf.researchr.org/track/fse-2026/fse-2026-how-to-submit

8.Make sure that in the camera-ready version, emails of all the authors are provided.

9.Make sure that in the camera-ready version, the authors need to be stocked individually as shown in this example:
https://www.acm.org/binaries/content/assets/publications/word_style/interim-template-style/interim-layout.pdf

10.Before submitting the camera-ready version, click check format for the submitted PDF in HotCRP, and fix ALL the warnings about the formatting requirement violations in HotCRP (e.g, fonts not embedded, wrong margin, wrong font sizes, Line height too small,
 bad font, etc.) NOTE:  if you receive a warning that the page limit should be 4 pages, you can safely ignore.

11.Make sure that the last page is balanced.

12.Make sure that you follow the page limit requirement of your track. You will not have an additional page for your camera-ready version if your track does not explicitly include this in the call for papers.